                <h2>Project activities and strategies </h2>
                <h4>1. Forming of Youth Peace Clubs </h4>
                <p>Viewing youth as a potential force for positive change, the project VIJANA WA AMANI will identify volunteer youth and regroup them in small groups that will form Youth Peace Clubs, in different entities and areas (villages), at Schools, Universities, Churches, Villages. Different ethnics groups and castes will be represented in each Youth Peace Club to improve the diversity of - and interaction between – participating. A total of 100 YPC will be formed in 5 territories ( Goma, Rutshuru, Masisi, Kelehe, Nyiragongo)</p>

                <h4>2. Developing youth capacities </h4>
                <p>The project will provide capacity building opportunities for 5000 youth in the thematic areas of peace-building, leadership, management, social mobilization and project management. 200 of these youth will participate in the Master Training of Trainers (TOT) program; these Master Trainers later will conduct 15 peace-building trainings for 100 Youth Peace Clubs members. Additionally, youth will learn mediation skills that allow them to facilitate non-violent conflict resolution</p>

                <h4>3. Building stronger networks between youth from different communities and areas.</h4>
                <p>Two general youth assemblies, 18 sports competitions and 12 cultural programs involving all youths will be organized through VIJANA WA AMANI project. These programs positively will contribute towards building good relationships, developing stronger networks, and narrowing differences among participating youth from different communities, ethnic groups and castes.</p>

                 <h4>4. Bridging the Gap between Adults, Decision-maker, government and Youth:</h4>
                <p>The project will facilitate over 36 coordination meetings, including 12 meetings with traditional decision-making bodies (local authorities, local government, local parliament, and community elders). Additionally, 50 parent-youth meetings will be held. The ensuing discussions will be instrumental in contributing to an improved level of understanding between - and to collective action involving - adults and youth, resulting in a higher representation of youth in community decision-making structures.</p>

                 <h4>5. Mobilizing Youth in Community Services:</h4>
                <p>Youth will contribute to the completion of Social Service Projects (SSPs): building community halls, water and sanitation, culverts and latrines; repairing agricultural roads and furniture; and, supporting livestock production and fish farming. In addition to providing basic services to communities, the SSPs will also help to build stronger relationships within the villages and other stakeholders, including NGOs and local government. Youth will contribute almost 8 hours per week the minimum contribution to the SSPs,</p>

                 <h4>6. Mobilizing Youth to Promote Peace and Reconciliation:</h4>
                <p>5000 youth will be mobilized to promote community peace and reconciliation through the (Peace talks) meetings, discussions, trainings, and SSPs; the production and airing of  radio broadcasting peace programs; participation in street dramas and cross/exposure visits; and, organizing and participating in  peace promotion competitions at schools and Universities.</p>
